Deep Explanation of the PPP Triplet in AgDR v0.2
The PPP Triplet is the philosophical and technical core of the entire AgDR standard. It is the smallest possible set of information that must be captured atomically with every agent decision to make accountability real, lasting, and legally meaningful.
Policy = PPP
(Provenance · Place · Purpose)
The meaning of each “P” is deliberately of the beholder. AgDR does not dictate definitions. It only requires that whatever meaning you (or your organization) assign to each P is captured verbatim at the exact moment of inference and frozen forever in the record.
1. Provenance – “Where we are today”
Deep meaning: The origin, authenticity, and current state of the decision.
What it captures at inference instant:

All relevant stakeholders and their human context (the “what’s in it for me” element)
The exact starting conditions and system state
Proof that this record was created at the true moment of inference

Why it matters:

Without clear provenance, no one can ever prove who was involved or what the real situation was.
It is the anchor that makes every later claim testable.
Legally, it directly satisfies the Canada Evidence Act reliability test and CBCA requirements for identifying who bears responsibility.

2. Place – “Where we are going”
Deep meaning: The intended destination and target state of the decision.
What it captures at inference instant:

The goal and desired outcome
The jurisdictional, operational, regulatory, and environmental boundary
The collective vision of “what success looks like” for the stakeholders

Why it matters:

Place defines the finish line. It gives context to every future audit or court review: did the agent’s action actually move toward the intended lawful outcome?
It directly supports purpose-limitation principles in privacy law and the fiduciary duty to act in the best interests of the corporation and its stakeholders.

3. Purpose – “Why we are going”
Deep meaning: The driving reason and motivation behind the decision.
What it captures at inference instant:

The explicit intent
The desired behaviour of the agent
The “how” we plan to reach the destination
The final closing principles of Beauty, Truth, and Wisdom (the philosophical and ethical anchor)

Why it matters:

Purpose connects raw computation to human duty. It is the missing link that lets existing fiduciary law (CBCA s.122 — acting honestly and in good faith) apply to machines without creating new legislation.
It turns an AI decision from a black-box output into a verifiable expression of intent.

How the PPP Triplet Is Captured
At the exact inference instant (the “i” point), the Atomic Kernel Inference (AKI) forces the full PPP triplet + reasoning trace + binary human delta chain into one indivisible kernel transaction.

Interrupts and preemption are disabled.
The entire payload is hashed, signed, and appended to the forward-secret Merkle chain.
The operation is either fully committed or fully rolled back — there is no partial state.

This atomic capture guarantees that the meaning of each P is frozen at the moment of thought and can never be rewritten or reconstructed later.
The Philosophy of “Meaning of the Beholder”
This openness is intentional and powerful. It allows:

A bank to define PPP in risk-management terms
A hospital to define it in clinical-ethics terms
A government agency to define it in public-interest terms

The standard remains universal while respecting local context and evolving values.
Legal and Practical Power
The PPP triplet + atomic capture + FOI escalation creates the first clean bridge between existing law and autonomous agents. Courts no longer need to guess intent — they simply ask: “Present the AgDR record.”
